What is a "CN"?
We interchangeably use it for host in a lot of places, "compute node"
Oh ok, so then, follow-up question: why is the BMC impersonating the compute node on NCSI links? And what does it mean to impersonate the compute node? Just curious lol

Our routers are configured in such a way that a machine gets a ::/64 address space, and all of the traffic is routed to the 0th address (address for the primary host). When the host is down, we need to be able to answer neighbor queries for the router so that we can route traffic to the BMC (our NICs have special rules to handle packet mirroring and routing of specific addresses to the BMC). Otherwise, the machine would become unreachable.
We used to also used to fully impersonate the IP of the host, and the NIC would handle only forwarding specific ports to the BMC. This was due to a lack of multi-address allocation for a machine.

Hmmmmmm so even if a host is down, you want STP and LLDP to get responses from the BMC, to keep the network topology from changing or something? But then...why would that change if they share the same link? Safe to say I don't have any concerns, just pestering you

Well, we don't use any of those protocols at the host level. But yes, we need to respond to the "primary" neighbor in those cases. We have some virtualization that doesn't faithfully re-implement the NIC behavior and the BMC and host end up on the same network segment without the fancy packet filtering rules. Since they both have different MAC addresses in this case this impersonation scheme makes it impossible to talk to the host. This is a workaround to make that configuration possible while preserving the impersonation behavior where it is needed.
